Good Chinese restaurant (not to be confused with Chinese takeout).   Good selections if dim sum as well as dinner food.   The venue is a lot smaller than some of the 8th avenue counterparts but the food more than make up for it (though it's hard to get a seat pre pandemic) due to the size.  Hopefully we can all dine in soon.

The service was good. The waitress was fast and prompt. They speak mainly Chinese but understood enough English. The food was good and ready reasonably quick to get to our table. Nothing was too salty, which is great considering other Chinese restaurants are often too salty. The table peanuts, like the ones in bars, were way too salty. The tea was fine. The men's restroom was average clean, no paper towels, just a air dryer. I would go again if I am in the neighborhood.
Can't wait to go back.

Serve traditional Chinese food, dishes are good to the point.  Service is always fast and workers are polite and keep your tea refill regularly.  Price is not bad compare to others in the area.  Location is convenient and easy to find parking.

My family and I are regulars at this friendly neighborhood restaurant serving truly authentic Cantonese dim sum and dishes. If you’re craving anything, the kitchen is happy to work with you!  The portions are generous and prices are affordable. It gets very busy on the weekends so be prepared to wait for a table. What I love most is that they make steamed parsley rice noodles with sweet soy to order, which is one of my favorite dim sum.

Great overall value at this buffet! Food is delicious at unbeatable price (dumplings to KILL for!). Friendly, attentive waitstaff, and clean facilities. The buffet’s selections are replenished frequently.

Leaving the 2 stars for dim sum. Food is okay.  I'm unhappy about the service. Cold day, morning tea with the kids. Since there were lots of empty tables, we asked for a table towards the inside rather than the table the waitress wanted seat us -- right in front of the door. She insisted the one by the door. Then a party of 3 walks in and gets seated at the empty tables. Like... really? Then at the end of our meal, we were still into our last bites of food and people were already clearing out our table and pulling on to the table cloth.... come on now. What kind of service is this? I grabbed half of the tips off the table when leaving. Never coming back.

Good dimsum at this restaurant but even better dinner entrees for family style. The staffs are friendly and nice. Atmosphere is laid back and chill. The food was pretty good, definitely recommend the fried yellow noodles with the stir fry of scallion and ginger lobster, the mayo fried shrimp with broccoli, cauliflower with fried squid, fried tofu with saucy mushrooms, saucy rib flaps with broccoli, stir fry snails and etc. Overall great place and you can byob. If you know what byob is yay for you.

A typical fare dim sum/ banquet style Chinese restaurant has been in the neighborhood for 2 decades or so. Over the years, it has changed through many hands -some good, some bad. This current kitchen staff is about average the food is a tad bit greasy, oil/ grease pools at the bottom of the plates.  The front house should really improve their communication skills with customers. Feel a bit brushed off as I'm an ABC, and is more polite when addressing my parents who are fluent in Cantonese.  Weekend dim sum wait is ridiculous, I rather go to another restaurant in Sun Set Park with better quality.  For dinner, appetizer gratis: salted and roasted peanuts, picked vegetables and dessert gratis: sweetened red bean soup, coconut jelly, and slices of oranges. Avoid the casserole clay pot dishes, just a bunch of stuff mixed in gravy sauce and the bottom is stuff with lettuce to give an appearance of fullness.
Came here for a small banquet.  The Beef Short Ribs are amazing.
Dim sum go go !

They have plenty of variety of dim sum during the day. Lovely steamed items of hai gau (shrimp dumplings) and fried items. The rice congee with pork and thousand year old egg is delish as well as their churn fun, rice noodle dishes. Singapore noodles were cooked well with plenty of ingredients. Definitely order the black sesame balls and the regular sesame balls as they are sweet and chewy as they should be. Everyone definitely were with full stomachs towards the end. Ok service a step up from the usual service of a busy chinese restaurant.
Excellent place to come for dim sum or a big family-style dinner – however, you might have to wait or share a table. Watch out for the Durian pastry!
